The study failed to depict #MPesa for what it really isâ€”a financial 'innovation' that enriches elites at the expense of the poor, while also shifting risks to the poor themselves, ensuring they will be most devastated by a future financial collapse. 11/

6th, the study does not have a control group, making it impossible to attribute the impacts to #MPesa alone. Also, they do not control for selection bias, have a small sample size, and ignore the fact that #MPesa agents are drawn to wealthier areas. 9/

5th, they claim that #MPesa quickly transfers cash within networks to those most in need, but ignore that this is dependent on the level of wealth within a network. In this sense #MPesa is more about helping the rich to deploy their wealth, feeding into inequality. 8/

4th, they argue that #MPesa clients benefit from integration into the formal financial system, but fail to consider wider issues of corporate power and legacies of imperialism. #MPesa is largely foreign-owned with the digitally-mined wealth being extracted from Kenya. 7/

3rd, they measure increases in incomes and savings, but fail to calculate increases in debt that are also attributable to #MPesa. This is a glaring omission considering that Kenya is facing dangerously high levels of over-indebtedness.  6/

2nd, they did not factor new entry (displacement) into their assessment. New enterprises facilitated by #MPesa inevitably take demand away from existing businesses. By ignoring this they make the erroneous assumption that supply creates its own demand (Say's Law). 5/

1st, they argue that #MPesa facilitates the move from agriculture to microenterprise, but apparently did not consider enterprise failure. Kenya has high levels of exit, meaning that many of the businesses must have failed with negative outcomes for households. 4/

and it costs a lot of money to send and withdraw the money. and that is how #Mpesa makes most of it's money. This is backward compared to how ordinary bank accounts operate. Yet, it is what many people prefer. Here is a lesson to be learnt.

see if I have some cash and I want to send to you, I can easily walk into a bank/agent and deposit to your account and you will have the money in an instant. With #Mpesa that isn't the case, I cannot deposit to your phone. I have to deposit to mine and then send to you.

#Mpesa is a great product, what has made it great however is taking away the one key feature of banking which is convenient and cheap and ends up making money off it. Yet their goal is banking the unbanked. how ironical.
